    tagline: 'The giant of Africa — a nation of 220 million stories.',
    narrative: `Nigeria did not exist before 1914. It was invented — assembled by British colonial administrators who drew a line around a vast territory containing hundreds of distinct ethnic groups, dozens of kingdoms, and two of the world's great religions, and called it a country. The name itself was coined by a British journalist. What is remarkable is not that Nigeria has struggled since independence in 1960, but that it has held together at all — and more than held together, become the most populous nation on the continent, the largest economy in Africa, and one of the most culturally generative societies on Earth.\n\nLong before the British arrived, this land was home to extraordinary civilizations. The Nok people were producing terracotta sculpture two thousand years ago. The Yoruba city of Ile-Ife was the spiritual center of one of the world's richest cosmologies. The Benin Kingdom produced bronze castings of such technical mastery that European scholars, when they first encountered them in 1897, initially refused to believe Africans had made them. The Hausa-Fulani sultanates of the north had been centers of Islamic learning and trans-Saharan trade for centuries. Nigeria's pre-colonial past is not a prologue to history — it is history.\n\nToday, Nigeria pulses with a creative energy that is reshaping global culture. Nollywood produces more films than any industry except Bollywood. Afrobeats, pioneered by Fela Kuti and carried into the 21st century by artists like Burna Boy and Wizkid, has become the world's most infectious popular music. The country's writers — Chinua Achebe, Wole Soyinka, Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie — have produced some of the defining literature of the postcolonial era. Nigeria's immense challenges — corruption, ethnic tension, poverty, insecurity — are real and profound. But so is its vitality. The country that holds one in six Africans is still writing its story.`,
