    tagline: 'The only African nation never colonized — ancient, proud, and defiant.',
    narrative: `Ethiopia is Africa's oldest independent nation and one of the oldest in the world. While virtually every other African country was carved up and ruled by European powers in the 19th century, Ethiopia stood alone — defeating Italy at the Battle of Adwa in 1896 in what remains the most significant African military victory over a European colonial power in history. Emperor Menelik II's triumph sent a shockwave through the colonial world and made Ethiopia a symbol of African dignity and resistance that resonated from the Caribbean to Harlem.\n\nBut Ethiopia's story begins long before Adwa. The Kingdom of Aksum, which flourished from the 1st to 7th centuries AD, was one of the great powers of the ancient world — trading with Rome, Persia, and India, minting its own coins, and adopting Christianity in the 4th century, making Ethiopia one of the world's first Christian nations. The ancient church of Lalibela, carved entirely out of solid rock in the 12th century, is one of humanity's most astonishing architectural achievements. Ethiopia claims to be the home of the Ark of the Covenant — a belief held with absolute sincerity by the Ethiopian Orthodox Church to this day.\n\nThe 20th century brought Ethiopia both triumph and catastrophe. Haile Selassie, the last emperor, became a global symbol — the messianic figure of the Rastafari movement, the dignified voice at the League of Nations appealing for help against Italian invasion in 1935. But his rule ended in a Marxist revolution in 1974, followed by decades of famine, war with Eritrea, and political upheaval. Yet Ethiopia endures — ancient, proud, contradictory, home to the source of the Blue Nile, the oldest human fossils on Earth, and coffee, which the world drinks by the billion cups daily without knowing it came from here.`,
