    narrative: `South Africa's story is one of the most dramatic of the 20th century: a country that institutionalized racism so thoroughly it gave the world a new word — apartheid — and then, against almost every prediction, dismantled it peacefully through one of history's most extraordinary negotiations. The man at the center of that transformation, Nelson Mandela, spent 27 years in prison and emerged not with vengeance but with a vision of reconciliation that astonished the world. When he became president in 1994, leading the country's first fully democratic election, it felt to many like a miracle.\n\nBut South Africa's history runs much deeper than the 20th century. This is the land where some of our earliest human ancestors walked — the Cradle of Humankind near Johannesburg has yielded fossils of Australopithecus dating back 3.5 million years. The San people, whose rock art covers cave walls across the country, have lived here for perhaps 100,000 years, making them among the oldest continuous cultures on Earth. The Zulu Kingdom under Shaka in the early 19th century was one of the most powerful military states in Africa — a warrior civilization whose fighting methods were studied by military historians for generations.\n\nThe wounds of apartheid have not fully healed. South Africa remains one of the most unequal societies on Earth, its wealth still concentrated along racial lines, its cities still divided by the geography of segregation. But it is also a country of extraordinary energy — its literature, its music, its constitutional democracy (considered one of the world's most progressive), its constitutional court, its Truth and Reconciliation Commission. South Africa showed the world that transformation is possible. The question it still wrestles with is whether transformation is sufficient.`,
