    tagline: 'Where the ancient world meets the modern Arab world.',
    narrative: `Modern Egypt sits atop one of the oldest civilizations in human history, and this weight is both its greatest asset and its deepest challenge. Cairo is a city of 20 million people built in the shadow of monuments that are 4,500 years old. The pyramids of Giza — still the only surviving Wonder of the Ancient World — rise from the desert at the edge of the city, visible from rooftops, a constant reminder that whatever Egyptians build today, their ancestors built something more enduring. This is a country that has been continuously inhabited, continuously significant, for longer than almost anywhere on Earth.\n\nModern Egypt was shaped by a series of occupations — Greek, Roman, Arab, Ottoman, French, British — each leaving its mark. The Arab conquest of 641 AD transformed the country most profoundly: Egypt became Arab-speaking and Muslim, the ancient language and religion fading until the Coptic Church became their only living trace. Napoleon's 1798 expedition — which brought scholars as well as soldiers — produced the Description de l'Égypte, the most comprehensive study of ancient Egypt ever made, and kickstarted the Egyptology that would eventually decode hieroglyphics and rediscover the ancient world. British occupation (1882–1952) built the infrastructure of a modern state while extracting its wealth and fueling a nationalism that found its voice in Gamal Abdel Nasser.\n\nNasser's Egypt — socialist, pan-Arab, fiercely independent — nationalized the Suez Canal in 1956 and became the center of gravity for Arab nationalism. He was followed by Sadat, who made peace with Israel and was assassinated for it; then Mubarak, whose 30-year autocracy ended in the 2011 revolution that for one extraordinary moment seemed to promise something new. Egypt's story is still unfolding — a nation navigating between its ancient identity, its Arab present, its Islamic faith, and the demands of a young, enormous, restless population.`,
