    narrative: `On March 6, 1957, Kwame Nkrumah stood before a jubilant crowd and declared: "Ghana, your beloved country, is free forever." It was a sentence that echoed across an entire continent. Ghana was the first sub-Saharan African country to gain independence from European colonial rule, and its liberation was not just a national event — it was a continental signal. If Ghana could be free, all of Africa could be free. Within a decade, more than thirty African nations had followed.\n\nThe territory that became Ghana was home to some of West Africa's greatest kingdoms. The Ashanti Empire, whose golden stool symbolized the soul of the nation, was a sophisticated state that controlled the gold and kola nut trades across the Sahara for centuries and resisted British conquest so fiercely that it took four wars to subdue it. The name "Ghana" itself was borrowed from the ancient Ghana Empire that flourished in what is now Mauritania and Mali — a deliberate act of historical pride, connecting the new nation to a pre-colonial grandeur.\n\nNkrumah's Ghana became the intellectual capital of pan-Africanism — the idea that Africa's liberation and Africa's unity were inseparable. He hosted freedom fighters, revolutionaries, and thinkers from across the diaspora. W.E.B. Du Bois, the great African-American intellectual, renounced his American citizenship and died in Accra in 1963. Today, Ghana is one of Africa's most stable democracies, its elections consistently praised as free and fair, its economy anchored by cocoa, gold, and a growing tech sector. It has become, again, a beacon — this time not of political liberation but of the possibility that African democracy can work.`,
