    tagline: 'Born in the cradle of humanity, raised on the shores of a great lake.',
    narrative: `Kenya sits at the crossroads of human history in the most literal sense. The Great Rift Valley that runs through its heart has yielded the oldest known fossils of our human ancestors — Homo habilis, Homo erectus, evidence of the long evolutionary journey that produced our species. The bones of our earliest relatives lie beneath the same soil where Kenyan marathon runners train, where flamingos crowd the soda lakes, where the Great Migration of wildebeest crosses the Mara River in one of nature's most spectacular annual events. To stand in Kenya is to stand in the place where humanity began.\n\nThe Swahili Coast — Kenya's Indian Ocean shore — was one of the medieval world's great trading networks. Arab, Indian, Persian, and Swahili merchants traded at ports like Mombasa for a thousand years before Europeans arrived, building a cosmopolitan civilization whose language, Swahili, blended Bantu grammar with Arabic vocabulary and became the lingua franca of East Africa. The slave trade that the Portuguese and later the Arabs ran through these ports devastated the interior; then British colonization, beginning in earnest in the 1880s, brought the railways that opened the highlands to white settlers and dispossessed the Kikuyu, Maasai, and other peoples of their land.\n\nThe Mau Mau uprising of the 1950s — a brutal insurgency against British rule, met with brutal British repression — forced Britain to accelerate decolonization. Independence came in 1963 under Jomo Kenyatta, himself a former detainee. Kenya has since become East Africa's economic hub, Nairobi its most cosmopolitan city, the country's distance runners its most globally recognized faces. Kenya holds a tension common to many African nations: between its extraordinary natural wealth and biodiversity, the creativity and ambition of its people, and the political corruption and inequality that have frustrated the promise of independence.`,
