    tagline: 'Where Africa meets Arabia meets Europe — a crossroads civilization.',
    narrative: `Morocco occupies one of the world's great crossroads. Africa's northwestern corner, separated from Europe by only 14 kilometers of water at the Strait of Gibraltar, it has been a meeting point of civilizations for millennia — Berber, Phoenician, Roman, Arab, Andalusian, Ottoman, French. Each wave left its mark, and the result is a culture of extraordinary richness and complexity: Arabic in language, Berber in its deepest roots, Andalusian in its art and architecture, French in its institutions, and African in its geography and its southward reach.\n\nThe Berbers — the Amazigh people — are Morocco's oldest inhabitants, present long before the Arab conquest of the 7th century AD. They absorbed Islam but preserved their language and customs, and today Tamazight is a co-official language, a recognition of what Moroccans always knew: that Arabization was a cultural overlay on a civilization that runs much deeper. The Almoravid and Almohad dynasties of the 11th–13th centuries, born in Morocco, built an empire that stretched from Senegal to Spain and briefly made Marrakech and Fez the intellectual capitals of the Western world.\n\nFez, whose medina is the largest car-free urban area in the world and a UNESCO World Heritage Site, contains one of the world's most extraordinary medieval cities — a labyrinth of souks, madrasas, mosques, and workshops where leather is still tanned in the same stone vats used a thousand years ago. The University of al-Qarawiyyin, founded in Fez in 859 AD, is considered by many scholars to be the world's oldest continuously operating university. Morocco navigates its modern identity — constitutional monarchy, Islamic state, African nation, Mediterranean country, economic reformer — with the particular confidence of a civilization that has been at the center of things for a very long time.`,
