    tagline: 'Kilimanjaro, Serengeti, Zanzibar — where the world\'s oldest stories were first told.',
    narrative: `Tanzania contains some of the most extraordinary places on Earth. Kilimanjaro, the highest peak in Africa, rises from the savanna like a white-capped island in the sky. The Serengeti supports the largest terrestrial mammal migration on the planet — 1.5 million wildebeest, 250,000 zebras, 500,000 gazelles moving in an endless circle across the plains. The Ngorongoro Crater, a collapsed supervolcano, shelters one of the densest concentrations of wildlife anywhere. Zanzibar, the spice island off the coast, perfumes the Indian Ocean with cloves and carries the memory of a thousand years of trade. And in the Olduvai Gorge, the paleoanthropologist Mary Leakey found the 1.8-million-year-old footprints of Homo habilis — the oldest record of a human ancestor walking upright on Earth.\n\nThe Swahili Coast city of Kilwa, on Tanzania's southern shore, was described by Ibn Battuta in the 14th century as one of the most beautiful cities in the world. It controlled the gold trade from Great Zimbabwe to the Arabian markets and was, at its peak, one of the wealthiest ports in the Indian Ocean world. The Arab slave trade that eventually devastated this coast — an estimated 1.7 million Africans sold through Zanzibar's slave market between 1830 and 1873 — left wounds that shaped the region's history and its relationship with Islam in complex, layered ways.\n\nJulius Nyerere, Tanzania's founding father, was one of Africa's most idealistic leaders. His philosophy of Ujamaa — African socialism built on traditional communal values — was visionary in conception but struggled in implementation. What endured was Nyerere's insistence on Swahili as the national language, a decision that gave Tanzania something rare in Africa: a genuinely shared national identity that transcends ethnic and regional divisions. Tanzania has been among the continent's most politically stable nations, its vast national parks and game reserves the foundation of an ecotourism industry that funds one of the world's most ambitious wildlife conservation programs.`,
