    narrative: `Japan did something in the 19th century that no other country has managed before or since: it looked at the industrializing Western powers threatening to colonize it, concluded that it needed to become like them to survive, and transformed itself from a feudal shogunate into a modern industrial nation within a single generation. The Meiji Restoration of 1868 was not merely a political change — it was a civilizational pivot. In the space of 30 years, Japan built railways, universities, a modern army and navy, a constitution, heavy industries, and a bureaucracy on the Western model, while deliberately preserving the cultural distinctiveness that kept Japan Japanese. It is the most rapid, deliberate national modernization in history.\n\nThe consequences of that modernization were mixed. By the early 20th century, Japan had defeated Russia in the Russo-Japanese War (1905) — the first time in the modern era that an Asian nation defeated a European great power — and was on its way to building an empire. The Pacific War that Japan launched against the United States, China, and the European colonial powers in the 1930s and 1940s produced extraordinary military success followed by catastrophic defeat: atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki on August 6 and 9, 1945, killed 200,000 people and ended the war in a week. Japan emerged from the ashes occupied, constitutionally prohibited from maintaining offensive military forces, and under an American-written democratic constitution — and proceeded to build the world's second-largest economy in three decades.\n\nJapan's cultural exports have reshaped global popular culture in ways unmatched by any non-English-speaking country. Anime, manga, Nintendo, Sony PlayStation, karaoke, sushi, ramen, Toyota, Honda — these are Japanese things that became global things. The aesthetic philosophy behind them — the pursuit of perfection in form, the acceptance of impermanence (mono no aware), the dignity of craftsmanship (shokunin) — is as Japanese as the objects themselves. Japan is a country that has turned the art of making things into a spiritual practice, and the world has noticed.`,
    legacy: 'Japan\'s post-war reconstruction from nuclear devastation to economic superpower is the most remarkable national recovery in modern history. Japanese manufacturing philosophy (kaizen, just-in-time production) transformed global industry. Anime, manga, and video games made Japan the world\'s largest exporter of popular culture after the United States.',
    achievements: [
      'Japan rebuilt from nuclear devastation to the world\'s second-largest economy in under 30 years',
      'Toyota invented lean manufacturing and just-in-time production — transforming global industry',
      'Japan has the world\'s highest life expectancy and one of its lowest crime rates',
      'Japanese bullet trains (Shinkansen), introduced in 1964, pioneered high-speed rail worldwide',
      'Nintendo, Sony, and Sega created the video game industry as a global cultural medium',
      'The Japanese constitution\'s Article 9 — renouncing war — is the most unusual national commitment in history',
    ],
