    tagline: 'The miracle on the Han River — from rubble to global cultural powerhouse in 70 years.',
    narrative: `In 1953, South Korea was one of the poorest countries on Earth. The Korean War had left the peninsula divided, Seoul half-destroyed, and the economy devastated. Per capita income was lower than Ghana's. There were virtually no industrial facilities, no significant natural resources, and a population of 21 million people who had lived under Japanese occupation for 35 years and then fought a devastating civil war. Seventy years later, South Korea has the world's 10th-largest economy, produces Samsung, Hyundai, LG, and Kia, and has launched a cultural wave that has made Korean pop music, cinema, television dramas, and food globally dominant in ways that few would have predicted a decade ago.\n\nThe transformation is one of the most extraordinary in economic history — compressed into a single lifetime. Park Chung-hee's authoritarian government of the 1960s and 1970s directed industrial policy with a precision that built entire industries from scratch — steel, shipbuilding, electronics, automobiles — in a development model that was brutal in its human costs but effective in its economic results. Korea's chaebols (family-owned conglomerates) were the instrument of this industrialization, and they remain dominant today, for better and for worse. The democracy movement that eventually replaced the authoritarian governments — culminating in the peaceful democratic transition of 1987 — showed that South Koreans wanted not just prosperity but freedom, and that development could not be permanently separated from rights.\n\nHallyu — the Korean Wave — is the 21st century's most surprising cultural phenomenon. BTS became the world's most popular music act. Parasite (2019) became the first non-English-language film to win the Academy Award for Best Picture. Squid Game became Netflix's most-watched show in history. Korean skincare routines are now followed by millions worldwide. None of this was predictable, and all of it reflects something real about South Korean culture — its intensity, its perfectionism, its capacity to take a form (pop music, horror film, melodrama) and push it to a level of craft and emotional commitment that crosses every cultural boundary.`,
    legacy: 'South Korea\'s economic transformation from one of the world\'s poorest to one of its richest countries in a single generation is the most rapid development success in history. The Korean Wave (Hallyu) has made Korean culture globally dominant in music, film, television, and food in the 21st century.',
