    tagline: 'A thousand years of resistance — the country that fought its way to independence.',
    narrative: `Vietnam has been fighting for its independence for most of its recorded history. The country spent 1,000 years as a province of China — from 111 BC to 938 AD — and has spent much of the time since defending its independence against further attempts at dominance. The Vietnamese genius for resistance — patient, determined, deeply rooted in a sense of national identity that survived a millennium of foreign rule — is the defining thread of the country's history. When the American War ended in 1975 with North Vietnamese tanks entering Saigon, it was the fourth major foreign power to be expelled from Vietnamese territory in the 20th century: first the French, then the Japanese, then the French again, then the Americans.\n\nVietnamese civilization, when not occupied, produced a distinctive and sophisticated culture. The áo dài, the Vietnamese national dress, is among the most elegant garments in the world. Vietnamese cuisine — the balance of fresh herbs, rice noodles, fish sauce, and chili that produces pho, bánh mì, and a hundred other dishes — is now recognized internationally as one of the world's great culinary traditions. The country's landscape — the limestone karsts of Ha Long Bay, the green terraces of the northern highlands, the Mekong Delta's water world — is among the most visually spectacular in Asia. The literature that emerged from the war years, particularly the poetry of Ho Chi Minh and Bao Ninh's novel The Sorrow of War, is among the most profound writing to emerge from any conflict.\n\nVietnam's economic transformation since Doi Moi ("renovation") in 1986 — a shift from a command economy to a market-oriented one while retaining Communist Party governance — has been extraordinary. Poverty rates have fallen from 58% in 1992 to under 5% today. Vietnam has become a major manufacturing hub and one of Asia's fastest-growing economies. The country that the United States spent ten years trying to bomb into submission has become one of the most pro-American countries in Asia, with 84% of Vietnamese expressing favorable views of the US in recent surveys — a fact that is either deeply ironic or deeply human, depending on your perspective.`,
