    tagline: 'Seventeen thousand islands, one nation — the world\'s largest archipelago.',
    narrative: `Indonesia is an improbable country. It consists of 17,000 islands (6,000 inhabited) spread across an arc of ocean wider than the continental United States, inhabited by 275 million people speaking over 700 distinct languages, practicing every major world religion, and sharing an identity that was, in its modern form, invented by nationalist leaders who declared independence in 1945. That this entity holds together as a functioning democracy — the world's third-largest, in fact — is, like India's, one of the more remarkable political facts of the modern era.\n\nThe islands of Indonesia were for centuries the source of the most valuable substances in the world: nutmeg, cloves, pepper, and cinnamon. The Spice Islands — the Maluku archipelago — were the original destination of Magellan's circumnavigation, of Columbus's failed westward voyage, of the entire European Age of Discovery. The Dutch East India Company (VOC), which controlled the spice trade for most of the 17th century, was willing to wage wars, commit massacres, and enslave populations to maintain its monopoly — which it did, at extraordinary human cost to the indigenous peoples of the Banda Islands. The Netherlands extracted wealth from what is now Indonesia for 350 years; the relationship was not partnership but extraction.\n\nIndonesia's independence, declared by Sukarno and Hatta on August 17, 1945, was followed by a four-year independence war against Dutch re-colonization that left 100,000 dead before the Netherlands recognized Indonesian sovereignty in 1949. Sukarno's Guided Democracy gave way to Suharto's New Order in 1966, a military dictatorship that killed 500,000–1,000,000 people during the anti-communist purge of 1965–66 — one of the Cold War's bloodiest events, carried out with American support. Suharto's fall in 1998 opened a democratic transition that has, with imperfections, held for 25 years. Indonesia's Pancasila — five principles that include nationalism, humanity, unity, democracy, and social justice, without specifying a state religion — remains one of the most thoughtful attempts to build a plural identity for a multifaith nation.`,
