    color: '#239F40',
    tagline: 'Ancient Persia reborn — the civilization that survived every empire.',
    narrative: `Iran is Persia. The names are different — "Iran" was formalized in 1935 — but the civilization is continuous: the same language (Persian), the same territory (roughly), the same cultural memory stretching back to the Achaemenid Empire of Cyrus the Great in the 6th century BC. Persia was conquered by Alexander the Great, then by Arab Muslim armies in the 7th century AD, then by Mongols, then by Timurids — and each time, the conquerors were absorbed into Persian civilization rather than the reverse. The Mongols who destroyed Baghdad in 1258 had, by the next generation, converted to Islam and begun producing Persian poetry. This cultural resilience — the capacity to absorb invaders and continue — is Iran's most remarkable characteristic.\n\nIslamic Iran became the center of a golden age. The 9th through 12th centuries produced Persian poets — Rumi, Hafez, Omar Khayyám, Ferdowsi — whose work is still read, quoted, and loved across the Persian-speaking world and beyond. Rumi, born in what is now Afghanistan but associated entirely with Persian culture, is now the best-selling poet in the United States. Avicenna (Ibn Sina), the polymath who wrote encyclopedias of medicine and philosophy that shaped both Islamic and European thought for centuries, was Persian. The architectural tradition that produced Isfahan's Imam Square — one of the most beautiful urban spaces in the world — was Persian.\n\nThe 1979 Islamic Revolution was one of the 20th century's most transformative political events — a mass popular uprising that overthrew a US-backed shah and produced a theocratic republic that has governed Iran for over 40 years, navigated a devastating war with Iraq (1980–1988), survived international isolation and crippling sanctions, and remained, for better and worse, the most consequential regional power in the Middle East. Iran's nuclear program, its support for proxy forces across the region, and its fundamental tension between the authority of clerics and the aspirations of a young, educated, and deeply discontented population make it simultaneously the most important and most misunderstood country in the Middle East.`,
