    color: '#E30A17',
    tagline: 'Where East meets West — the bridge and the battlefield of civilization.',
    narrative: `Turkey occupies one of history's most consequential pieces of real estate. The Anatolian peninsula is the land bridge between Europe and Asia, and whoever controls it controls the chokepoint between two worlds. This is why Anatolia has been fought over for five thousand years: by Hittites and Egyptians, by Greeks and Persians, by Romans and Parthians, by Crusaders and Seljuks, by Byzantines and Ottomans. Istanbul — the city on the strait — was Constantinople, capital of the Byzantine Empire and before that of the Roman Empire, and before that Byzantium, founded by Greek colonists. Every great power that has dominated Eurasia has had to reckon with this city. It remains, today, the only city in the world that sits on two continents.\n\nMustafa Kemal Atatürk — the founding father of the Turkish Republic — undertook one of the 20th century's most radical national transformations. After the Ottoman Empire's collapse and the catastrophic Greek-Turkish War (which ended with the 1923 Lausanne Treaty and a brutal population exchange), Atatürk built a new country on explicitly secular, Western-facing principles. He replaced the Ottoman script with the Latin alphabet. He abolished the Sultanate and the Caliphate. He gave women the vote in 1934 — before France or Switzerland. He moved the capital from Istanbul to the new planned city of Ankara in Anatolia, deliberately turning the country's back on its Ottoman imperial legacy. Whether this transformation was liberation or imposition — there were losses as well as gains — is an argument Turks are still having.\n\nTurkey in the 21st century is a country of profound tensions: between secularism and Islamic politics, between democratic norms and authoritarian consolidation, between Western alliances (NATO membership since 1952) and a growing aspiration to independent regional power. Erdoğan's Turkey has been both more religiously conservative and more regionally assertive than any government since Atatürk, projecting power into Syria, Libya, Azerbaijan, and the Aegean in ways that have complicated every relationship it has. Turkey is simultaneously the bridge between civilizations and the country that cannot decide which side of the bridge it is on.`,
    legacy: 'Constantinople/Istanbul was the capital of two of history\'s greatest empires — Rome\'s eastern continuation and the Ottoman state. The Hagia Sophia, built by Byzantines and converted to a mosque twice, is one of architecture\'s greatest achievements. Atatürk\'s secular nationalist model influenced virtually every modernizing state in the Muslim world.',
