    color: '#A51931',
    tagline: 'The Land of Smiles — the only Southeast Asian nation never colonized.',
    narrative: `Thailand's most remarkable political achievement is the one you cannot see: it was never colonized. While every other mainland Southeast Asian nation fell to European imperial power — Vietnam, Laos, Cambodia to France; Myanmar to Britain — the Kingdom of Siam survived through a combination of shrewd diplomacy, strategic modernization, and the good fortune of being sandwiched between British and French spheres of influence such that neither power could afford to let the other have it. King Chulalongkorn (Rama V), who ruled from 1868 to 1910, modernized Siam's institutions, infrastructure, and administrative system while maintaining national sovereignty — one of the most successful defensive modernizations in Asian history.\n\nThai civilization runs much deeper than the modern state. The kingdoms of Sukhothai (13th–15th centuries) and Ayutthaya (14th–18th centuries) were among Southeast Asia's most sophisticated polities, producing Buddhist art, architecture, and literature of great refinement. Ayutthaya, at its peak in the 17th century, was one of the largest cities in the world — a cosmopolitan trading center visited by Portuguese, Dutch, French, Chinese, and Japanese merchants. When the Burmese sacked and burned it in 1767, the loss was catastrophic — not just politically but culturally, destroying irreplaceable manuscripts, art, and the accumulated records of four centuries.\n\nModern Thailand is defined by the constitutional monarchy, the Theravada Buddhist faith that organizes daily life from the village temple to the royal palace, and Bangkok — one of Asia's most chaotic, vibrant, and irresistible megacities. Thai food — the balance of sweet, sour, salty, and spicy that produces tom yum, pad thai, and green curry — has become one of the world's most beloved cuisines. Thai massage is practiced on every continent. The country has suffered repeated cycles of military coup and attempted democracy, but the Thai spirit — the genuine warmth and resilience captured, however imperfectly, by the "Land of Smiles" cliché — remains one of Asia's most generous and enduring cultural gifts.`,
    legacy: 'Thailand\'s successful defense of sovereignty against European colonialism is a model of adaptive diplomacy. Theravada Buddhism, preserved and propagated from Thailand, shapes the daily life of 130 million people across Southeast Asia. Thai cuisine has become one of the world\'s most globally successful food cultures.',
